          'question' => 'How heavy was the biggest European coin really issued into circulation?',
          'answer' => 'In modern age, referring to Europe, among the coins that really circulated we can mention one whose weight exceeds 350 grams. It is a gold coin, a multiple of 105 sequins, issued by the Venice mint under the Doge Ludovico Manin (1789-1797), on which appears the traditional iconography of the Doge kneeling in front of  St. Mark and of  Blessing Christ contained in a stars almond. Changing continent, we have to remember also some really special coins, not only for their significant weight, but especially for their shape really unusual. We are talking about bronze and silver copies with the shape of a sword,  a hoe and a star circulating in China until the 1930s.',
